<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="524" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,970,2040]" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1151,1177]" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Etymology.</emphasis>
We named this species in honor of Prof. Dr. Paulo De Marco Júnior, professor at the Universidade Federal de 
<collectingRegion box="[277,345,1186,1212]" country="Brazil" name="Goias" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Goiás</collectingRegion>
, friend and encourager of the work of all authors, and mainly for his dedication to science in the last four decades.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="525" pageId="13" pageNumber="524" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,970,2040]" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,484,1258,1285]" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">
Description of 
<typeStatus box="[374,479,1259,1285]" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[491,552,1258,1284]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Head</emphasis>
. Labrum and anteclypeus sky blue, genae and outer surface of mandible greenish–blue, postclypeus dark brown to black, epicranium anterior 2/3 (up to the level of lateral ocellus) black with metallic green reflections, posterior 1/3 reddish–brown (
<figureCitation box="[774,877,1330,1357]" captionStart="FIGURE 35" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1370,1394]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,843,1337]" captionTargetId="figure-33@23.[153,1434,841,1347]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 35. Lestes demarcoi sp. nov.: Head—dorsal view—A—male, B—female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5027084" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5027084/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Fig. 35A</figureCitation>
), rear of head pale yellow, antennae: scape, ventral half of pedicel and flagellum brown, dorsal half of pedicel black (
<figureCitation box="[887,992,1366,1393]" captionStart="FIGURE 35" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1370,1394]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,843,1337]" captionTargetId="figure-33@23.[153,1434,841,1347]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 35. Lestes demarcoi sp. nov.: Head—dorsal view—A—male, B—female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5027084" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5027084/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Fig. 35A</figureCitation>
). Labium and maxillae pale yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,970,2040]" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">
<emphasis box="[199,280,1402,1428]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Thorax</emphasis>
. Prothorax brown, with two pale blue spots on each side (
<figureCitation box="[967,1075,1402,1429]" captionStart="FIGURE 35" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1370,1394]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,843,1337]" captionTargetId="figure-33@23.[153,1434,841,1347]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 35. Lestes demarcoi sp. nov.: Head—dorsal view—A—male, B—female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5027084" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5027084/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Fig. 35A</figureCitation>
); pterothorax: middorsal carina brown, followed by a brown middorsal stripe which is followed by a black with green metallic reflections stripe, which is followed by a narrow brown stripe followed by a broad pale blue stripe limited ventrally by the mesopleural suture; metepisternum brown, metepimeron, metinfraepisternum pale blue (
<figureCitation box="[1052,1158,1510,1537]" captionStart="FIGURE 36" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,1419,1832]" captionTargetId="figure-49@23.[153,1434,1419,1832]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 36. Lestes demarcoi sp. nov.: Thorax—lateral view—A—male, B—female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5027086" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5027086/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Fig. 36A</figureCitation>
). Legs: coxae pale blue, external surface of femora, tarsi and tarsal claws black, external surface of tibiae and internal surface of femora and tibiae pale.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,970,2040]" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">
<emphasis box="[199,305,1618,1644]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Abdomen</emphasis>
. S1–S8 dorsally black with the exception of basal 2/3 of S1 blue, a narrow pale medial line in S2 and a pale basal annulus in S2–8, bluish laterally, S9 dark brown dorso–laterally with 2 pale dots in each side, S10 dark brown. Penis as in 
<figureCitation box="[364,446,1690,1717]" captionStart="FIGURE 41" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1174,1198]" captionTargetBox="[240,1348,188,1144]" captionTargetId="figure-17@27.[231,1355,181,1151]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 41. Penis: Lestes demarcoi sp. nov.: A—lateral view, B—ectal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5027098" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5027098/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
. Appendages black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,970,2040]" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Measurements (in mm). Total length (incl. apps) 44: abdomen (incl. apps) 35, hindwing 22, cerci 2.00, paraprocts 0.8.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,970,2040]" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,475,1798,1825]" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">
Description of 
<typeStatus box="[373,470,1799,1825]" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">allotype</typeStatus>
.
</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[481,542,1798,1824]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Head</emphasis>
. Labrum sky blue, genae and outer surface of mandible greenish–blue, anteclypeus dark blue, postclypeus dark brown to black, epicranium anterior 2/3 (up to the level of lateral ocellus) black with metallic green reflections, posterior 1/3 reddish brown (
<figureCitation box="[774,875,1870,1897]" captionStart="FIGURE 35" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1370,1394]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,843,1337]" captionTargetId="figure-33@23.[153,1434,841,1347]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 35. Lestes demarcoi sp. nov.: Head—dorsal view—A—male, B—female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5027084" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5027084/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Fig. 35B</figureCitation>
), rear of head pale, antennae: scape, ventral 3/5 of pedicel pale, 2/5 dorsal of pedicel and flagellum brown, (
<figureCitation box="[792,895,1906,1933]" captionStart="FIGURE 35" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1370,1394]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,843,1337]" captionTargetId="figure-33@23.[153,1434,841,1347]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 35. Lestes demarcoi sp. nov.: Head—dorsal view—A—male, B—female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5027084" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5027084/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Fig. 35B</figureCitation>
). Labium and maxillae pale.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,970,2040]" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">
<emphasis box="[199,280,1942,1968]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Thorax</emphasis>
. Prothorax and thorax as in 
<typeStatus box="[596,694,1942,1968]" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation box="[709,812,1942,1969]" captionStart="FIGURE 36" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,1419,1832]" captionTargetId="figure-49@23.[153,1434,1419,1832]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 36. Lestes demarcoi sp. nov.: Thorax—lateral view—A—male, B—female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5027086" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5027086/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="524">Fig. 36B</figureCitation>
). Legs: coxae pale blue, external surface of femora pale with a fine black longitudinal line, tibiae pale, tarsi and tarsal claws black, internal surface of femora and tibiae pale.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5027040" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5027040" box="[151,1238,594,618]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5027040/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="525" startId="14.[151,250,594,618]" targetBox="[152,1436,182,570]" targetPageId="14">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1238,594,618]" box="[151,1238,594,618]" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,288,594,618]" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">FIGURE 14.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Lencioni &amp; Neiss &amp; Dutra &amp; Furieri &amp; Juen &amp; Batista &amp; Vilela, 2021" authorityName="Lencioni &amp; Neiss &amp; Dutra &amp; Furieri &amp; Juen &amp; Batista &amp; Vilela" authorityYear="2021" box="[294,459,594,618]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="14" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demarcoi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[294,459,594,618]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">Lestes demarcoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[465,545,594,618]" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[465,545,594,618]" pageId="14" pageNumber="525" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
: A—Appendages, lateral view; B—Appendages, mediodorsal view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,664,1194]" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">
<emphasis box="[199,305,664,690]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">Abdomen</emphasis>
. S1–8 dorsally dark brown to black with the exception of basal 1/3 of S1 blue, a narrow pale basal annulus in S2–8, S1–8 bluish laterally, S3–6 the dark dorsal area expanded laterally near the apex, in S7 the dark dorsal area expanded laterally in both extremities, S9–10 dark brown. Valves of ovipositor brown and cerci black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,664,1194]" box="[199,1090,772,799]" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">Measurements (in mm). Total length (incl. apps) 42: abdomen 33, hindwing 23.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="525" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,664,1194]" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,465,808,834]" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
The easiest character to separate all Brazilian species from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lencioni &amp; Neiss &amp; Dutra &amp; Furieri &amp; Juen &amp; Batista &amp; Vilela" authorityYear="2021" box="[1170,1356,808,834]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="14" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demarcoi">
<emphasis box="[1170,1356,808,834]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">Lestes demarcoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is, the male’s cerci. Using this character, males of the new species form a cohesive group with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sjostedt" authorityYear="1918" box="[1128,1238,844,870]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="14" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falcifer">
<emphasis box="[1128,1238,844,870]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">L. falcifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hagen" authorityYear="1862" box="[1291,1387,845,870]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="14" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pictus">
<emphasis box="[1291,1387,845,870]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">L. pictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lencioni &amp; Neiss &amp; Dutra &amp; Furieri &amp; Juen &amp; Batista &amp; Vilela" authorityYear="2021" box="[180,315,880,906]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="14" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demarcoi">
<emphasis box="[180,315,880,906]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">L. demarcoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the cercus is much longer than the length of S10, compared with the other two species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,664,1194]" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">
The paraproct of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lencioni &amp; Neiss &amp; Dutra &amp; Furieri &amp; Juen &amp; Batista &amp; Vilela" authorityYear="2021" box="[388,521,916,942]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="14" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demarcoi">
<emphasis box="[388,521,916,942]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">L. demarcoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is shorter than half the length of the cercus, while in the other two species is longer. In mediodorsal view, the apical portion of the cercus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lencioni &amp; Neiss &amp; Dutra &amp; Furieri &amp; Juen &amp; Batista &amp; Vilela" authorityYear="2021" box="[777,911,952,978]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="14" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demarcoi">
<emphasis box="[777,911,952,978]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">L. demarcoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is ovoid while in the other two is finger–like.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,664,1194]" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">
We suggest caution in determining 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[602,672,989,1014]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="14" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[602,672,989,1014]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">Lestes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
females when they are collected not associated with males and we suggest the joint use of pectoral color patterns (
<figureCitation box="[678,759,1024,1050]" captionStart="FIGURE 39" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[367,1222,183,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-17@25.[366,1222,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 39. Basal plate of ovipositor (The basal plate was kept in color while the rest was converted to grayscale to facilitate the visualization of the differences between species): A—Lestes dichrostigma, B—Lestes forficula, C—Lestes minutus, D— Lestes paulistus, E—Lestes pictus, F—Lestes tricolor, G—Lestes undulatus, H—Lestes demarcoi sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5027092" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5027092/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
) with the shape of the basal plates of the ovipositor (
<figureCitation box="[1347,1428,1024,1050]" captionStart="FIGURE 38" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1850,1874]" captionTargetBox="[232,1354,953,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-59@24.[231,1356,944,1826]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 38. Female basal plate of ovipositor, with three configurations found in the known Brazilian species of Lestes: 1 (Lestes dichrostigma, Lestes pictus, Lestes tricolor and Lestes undulatus), 2 (Lestes forficula and Lestes paulistus) and 3 (Lestes minutus and Lestes demarcoi sp. nov.). Parts are named as follows: D—dorsal side, A—anterior side, V—ventral side, P—posterior side, PD—dorsal section of posterior side, PV—ventral section of posterior side, AP—Acute process (as defined in Westfall &amp; May (1996)), VA—anterior section of ventral side and VP—posterior section of ventral side." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5027090" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5027090/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
) for it.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,664,1194]" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">
The female of the new species belongs, together with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[819,939,1097,1122]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="14" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis box="[819,939,1097,1122]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">L. minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in a group where the posterior and ventral sides of the basal plate of ovipositor are divided in two sections each. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lencioni &amp; Neiss &amp; Dutra &amp; Furieri &amp; Juen &amp; Batista &amp; Vilela" authorityYear="2021" box="[952,1135,1132,1158]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="14" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demarcoi">
<emphasis box="[952,1135,1132,1158]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">Lestes demarcoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[1287,1406,1133,1158]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="14" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis box="[1287,1406,1133,1158]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">L. minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having the posterior section of the ventral side smaller than the anterior section.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
